{The position and story (see the main text) is taken from the book
"Begebenheiten am Schachbrett" by Albin Pötzsch, a great German columnist in
the vein of Kurt Richter or Dr. Tröger. The book collects (in German) many of
his columns from "Schach-Magazin 64", the magazine of Otto Borik. My source's
original column was first published in 2011, but Pötzsch usually reports
accurately based on the big chess library he has at home. - Master Alekhine
was to move, hoping for the variation, but due to his opponent's confusion
lost.} 1. e6 Nxe6 $1 ({Alekhine hoped for} 1... fxe6 2. dxe6 Nxe6 3. Nxe6 Bxe6
4. Kg3 a5 5. Kf4 a4 6. Ke5 Bf7 $2 7. Kd4 a3 8. Kc3 a2 9. Kb2 $11 {, believing
that the endgame was already a draw after 3.-B:e6, making this an example of
the Réti maneuver. However, there is more as shown below.}) (1... fxe6 2. dxe6
Nxe6 3. Nxe6 Bxe6 4. Kg3 a5 ({First of all, a nowadays well-known win is set
up with} 4... Kxf6 5. Kf4 Bf5 $19 {and the extra Ph3 does not matter. White
never can reach a1.}) 5. Kf4 a4 6. Ke5 Bd7 $3 ({or similarly} 6... Bb3 $19) ({
Alekhine thought that the bishop must move and it is a draw because of} 6... a3
7. Kxe6 a2 8. f7 $11 {but as we will see, even with the bishop moving Black
can win.}) 7. Kd4 (7. Kd6 Kxf6 $19) 7... a3 8. Kc3 Ba4 $1 $19 {. Interestingly
for this bishop setup (Ba4/Pa3, with reversed colors) J. Gunst won the 1st
prize in the Helsinki Chess Club tourney (for endgame studies) 1926. So it
seems that Gunst "invented" it 12 years after this game, with Alekhine not
finding it in his analysis. This shows that Alekhine missed not one but two
opportunities for endgame studies immortality by not creating such
compositions from the possibilities in this game. For someone who always
complained on how his opponents restricted him from showing his ideas, this
would have been an obvious step to take - why he didn't, we might never know.})
2. dxe6 Bxe6 {and White resigned.} 0-1

