{(S.S. 48) This study won the first semester 1938 tourney of Shakhmaty and has
become widely reprinted but likely won't be known to everyone. White is to
move and win, and with Black threatening to play 1.-Be5 to rely on winning the
queen which can't move because of checkmate on h8 this is not easy.} 1. Kh6 $1
(1. Kg7 $2 Be5 {Notice this position of mutual zugzwang. White to move can't
win, Black to move will lose.} 2. b4 (2. c4 $2 Bxf6+ 3. gxf6 b4 $19) 2... Bh2
3. Qf1 (3. g6 $2 Be5 $19) (3. c4 $2 bxc4 4. b5 Be5 5. b6 Bxf6+ 6. gxf6 c3 7. b7
Kd7 8. Kxf8 Kc7 $19) 3... Be5+ 4. Qf6 $11) ({The direct approach only leads to
a draw:} 1. g6 $2 Be5 2. Qxe5+ dxe5 3. g7 f5 4. exf5 Kf7 5. gxf8=Q+ Kxf8 6. c4
bxc4 7. bxc4 e4 8. c5 e3 9. c6 Ke7 10. f6+ Kxf6 11. c7 e2 12. c8=Q e1=Q 13.
Qf8+ Kg5 $11) (1. Qf1 $2 Be5 $11 {and the checkmate threat forces White to
give perpetual check.}) 1... Be5 2. Kg7 $1 {The position from the try is
reached, but Black is to move.} Bh2 (2... Bxf6+ 3. gxf6 $18 {and the rook
falls.}) 3. c4 $1 ({Knowing how studies work, you might be inclined to make
the most crazy move. It doesn't work here... yet:} 3. e5 $2 Bxe5 4. c4 b4 $19)
(3. b4 $2 Be5 $19) 3... bxc4 (3... b4 4. c5 $1 $18) 4. e5 $3 (4. bxc4 $2 Be5
$19) 4... Bxe5 5. bxc4 Bxf6+ (5... Bh2 6. c5 $18) 6. gxf6 Rh8 7. Kxh8 Kd7 8.
Kg8 $1 ({As Marco Campioli showed, White also can just wait:} 8. Kh7 $1 Ke6 9.
Kg7 $18) ({The final mutual zugzwang is easier to spot:} 8. Kg7 Ke6 $19) 8...
Ke6 9. Kg7 1-0

